cganhe glo

9.2

  • Support using a custom fs object, which is passed to PathScurry

9.1

  • Bring back the root option, albeit with slightly different semantics than in v8 and before.
  • Support { absolute:false } option to explicitly always return relative paths. An unset absolute setting will still return absolute or relative paths based on whether the pattern is absolute.
  • Add magicalBraces option to treat brace expansion as "magic" in the hasMagic function.
  • Add dotRelative option
  • Add escape() and unescape() methods

9.0

This is a full rewrite, with significant API and algorithm changes.

High-Level Feature and API Surface Changes

  • Only support node 16 and higher.
  • Promise API instead of callbacks.
  • Exported function names have changed, as have the methods on the Glob class. See API documentation for details.
  • Accept pattern as string or array of strings.
  • Hybrid module distribution.
  • Full TypeScript support.
  • Exported Glob class is no longer an event emitter.
  • Exported Glob class has walk(), walkSync(), stream(), streamSync(), iterate(), iterateSync() methods, and is both an async and sync Generator.
  • First class support for UNC paths and drive letters on Windows. Note that glob patterns must still use / as a path separator, unless the windowsPathsNoEscape option is set, in which case glob patterns cannot be escaped with \.
  • Paths are returned in the canonical formatting for the platform in question.
  • The hasMagic method will return false for patterns that only contain brace expansion, but no other "magic" glob characters.

title: build: Enhance Codespaces
body:
This PR:

- Makes `make argoexec-image` run in just a few seconds when rebuilding from cache. The `.git` folder gets modified every time you run git. This mean that the Docker caches being invalidated. `GIT_COMMIT` etc must be passed as Docker build .args
- Codespaces is not very polished. E.g. the "universal" image is not "universal" because it does not work on Apple Silicon.
- I've pinned Node to 16. While both 16 and 18 are LTS, 18 has the legacy SSL issue, to which there does not appear to be any simple fix.

If pre-built, you can start a Codespace instantly. When not pre-built, it takes several minutes.

title: fix: panic in offline linter + handling stdin
body:
Follow-up to https://github.com/argoproj/argo-workflows/pull/10059 and https://github.com/argoproj/argo-workflows/pull/10559

The offline linter is working well in ideal scenarios, I am linting a set of files/directory in 5 seconds where it used to take ~5 minutes

However, I did find issues after testing some more:
Given an non-existent file, it panics (I inverted the `info.IsDir()` statement and the one checking for errors) 
There's a disconnect between the `filepath.Walk` in the linter and the one building the offline client which means that there were other issues (such as stdin not working)

To fix those issues once and for all, I extracted the walk func to a common path (`file.WalkManifests`); that way, we are sure that changes are always reflected in both locations

I also added some tests for non-existent files as well as offline linting from stdin

  • Added nil coalescing operator ??.

Example:

user?.Name ?? "Anonymous"

v1.11.1

  • Fixed abs() for positive numbers

v1.11.0

Expr – an expression language for Go.

This release introduces a new API for defining functions inside Expr - expr.Function.

From an Expr expression is already possible to call any Go methods and functions, but Expr has to use reflect package in doing such calls. In previous releases, Expr added a special case for func (...any) any to avoid using reflect. But such functions lack type information. With newly added expr.Function option now it's possible to define a fast function with optional types! Read more in the docs.

atoi := expr.Function(
	"atoi",
	func(params ...any) (any, error) {
		return strconv.Atoi(params[0].(string))
	},
	new(func(string) int),
)

program, err := expr.Compile(atoi("42"), atoi)

  • Added bool condition optimization.
  • Added support for comments // and /* ... */.
  • Added support for negative indexes list[-1].
  • Predicate brackets are now optional all(list, .values > 0).

title: fix: exit handler variables don't get resolved correctly. Fixes #10393
body:
Signed-off-by: Jiacheng Xu <xjcmaxwellcjx@gmail.com>

Fixes #10393
 
This PR fixes the issue that exit handler variables(https://argoproj.github.io/argo-workflows/variables/#exit-handler) `workflow.status` and `workflow.failures` don't get resolved correctly.

The root cause of this issue is that the above 2 parameters will only be added to the global parameter map when the exit handler completes. If the expressions that contains the above 2 parameters are evaluated when they don't exist, Expr will evaluate them according to the zero value of map (nil) (https://github.com/antonmedv/expr/issues/330), for example:

`{{= workflow.status == "Succeeded" ? "SUCCESSFUL": "FAILED" }}`

When `workflow.status` doesn't exist in the parameter map, it will be evaluated as `nil` and the above expression becomes:

`{{ nil == "Succeeded" ? "SUCCESSFUL" : "FAILED" }}`

It will return `FAILED`.

This PR skips the expression evaluation if the above parameters are not in the parameter map, and only evaluates the expressions when exit handlers complete, and parameters are added to the map.
